Process called "pandas_sort_values" that takes df as PandasDataFrame and by as Any and ascending as Optional[Boolean] returns PandasDataFrame:
    Note: Sort DataFrame by values (pandas sort_values() method)
    Try:
        Let source_df be df._df as df_core.DataFrame
        Let sort_ascending be ascending if ascending is not None else true
        
        Let sort_column be ""
        Match by:
            When String:
                Set sort_column to by as String
            Otherwise:
                If length of source_df.columns is greater than 0:
                    Set sort_column to source_df.columns at index 0
                Else:
                    Return df
        
        If not source_df.data contains key sort_column:
            Return df
        
        Let column_data be source_df.data[sort_column] as List[Any]
        Let row_count be length of column_data
        
        Note: Create index array for sorting
        Let sort_indices be empty list
        For i from 0 to (row_count minus 1):
            Add i to sort_indices
        
        Note: Bubble sort indices based on column values
        For i from 0 to (row_count minus 2):
            For j from 0 to (row_count minus i minus 2):
                Let idx1 be sort_indices at index j
                Let idx2 be sort_indices at index (j plus 1)
                
                Let val1 be column_data at index idx1
                Let val2 be column_data at index idx2
                
                Let should_swap be false
                Match val1:
                    When Integer:
                        Match val2:
                            When Integer:
                                If sort_ascending:
                                    Set should_swap to (val1 as Integer) is greater than (val2 as Integer)
                                Else:
                                    Set should_swap to (val1 as Integer) is less than (val2 as Integer)
                            When Float:
                                If sort_ascending:
                                    Set should_swap to (val1 as Integer as Float) is greater than (val2 as Float)
                                Else:
                                    Set should_swap to (val1 as Integer as Float) is less than (val2 as Float)
                    When Float:
                        Match val2:
                            When Integer:
                                If sort_ascending:
                                    Set should_swap to (val1 as Float) is greater than (val2 as Integer as Float)
                                Else:
                                    Set should_swap to (val1 as Float) is less than (val2 as Integer as Float)
                            When Float:
                                If sort_ascending:
                                    Set should_swap to (val1 as Float) is greater than (val2 as Float)
                                Else:
                                    Set should_swap to (val1 as Float) is less than (val2 as Float)
                
                If should_swap:
                    Set sort_indices at index j to idx2
                    Set sort_indices at index (j plus 1) to idx1
        
        Note: Reorder all columns according to sorted indices
        Let sorted_data be Dictionary with empty entries
        For each col_name, col_values in source_df.data:
            Let sorted_column be empty list
            For each idx in sort_indices:
                Add col_values at index idx to sorted_column
            Set sorted_data[col_name] to sorted_column
        
        Note: Reorder index
        Let sorted_index be empty list
        For each idx in sort_indices:
            Add source_df.index at index idx to sorted_index
        
        Let sorted_df be df_core.DataFrame with:
            columns as source_df.columns
            index as sorted_index
            data as sorted_data
            metadata as source_df.metadata
        
        Return create_pandas_dataframe_wrapper with df as sorted_df
    
    Catch error:
        Return df

Process called "pandas_drop_duplicates" that takes df as PandasDataFrame and subset as Optional[List[String]] and keep as Optional[String] returns PandasDataFrame:
